text: Quick! A recipe just told you to cook something over medium heat. Your stove knob is marked with numbers from one to nine, so that means you should pick number four or five, right? Not necessarily. A gas stove's five is stronger than an electric five. This tiny burner's five is weaker than the big one's five. And then to cap it all off, each burner has its own idiosyncrasies like this one, where the difference between medium low and medium high is just a tiny turn of the knob. Instead of prescribing numbers, let me demystify what recipe writers usually mean when they tell you to cook something over a certain heat level. First, warm. A pan set to warm should just barely hold its contents above body temp. You can melt butter slowly and it won't foam. You can hold warm water in a pot without generating any bubbles. This setting is for when you need to keep food warm without changing its appearance. Think hollandaise sauce that needs to remain fluid and pourable without cooking down. On warm, you can touch the pan for a second without hurting yourself. Next up, low. A pot of water set to low will eventually generate tiny, infrequent bubbles. At this temp, butter will melt and potentially foam, but it won't brown. You won't be able to touch the pan with your full hand, but maybe you could handle a single finger for a second without screaming. Frying an egg on low heat will cook it through like a white and yellow egg emoji, but it won't yield dark brown crispy edges. You use low heat for simmering stock all day or for cooking oatmeal without scorching the bottom. The tiny bubbles that only rise every now and then are great for poaching something really delicate like a piece of fish. How about medium-low? Bubbling liquids in a medium-low pot are still gentle but continuously forming and popping. At medium-low heat, oil will not smoke, but it will loosen up and flow freely like water. Food will cook, and veggies will soften, but they won't really take on color. Medium-low is good for over-easy eggs. The white edges will flutter and bubble instead of being totally still like for the emoji egg. It's the heat level that I use when I'm cooking something that takes a long time to cook, and I want to speed it up without ruining it.
